  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_7",
      "text": "WORKFLOW: correlation & relationships. Which variables move together, and how? Correlation computes every pairwise coefficient among the wired columns; on 'auto' it uses Spearman (rank / monotonic) if any column fails a normality check, else Pearson (linear), so the whole matrix stays on one comparable method. Read three things: (1) STRENGTH and DIRECTION from the heatmap — deep blue/red = strong negative/positive, pale = weak; (2) LINEAR vs MONOTONIC — the pairs plot's scatterplots show whether a relationship is a straight line (Pearson-appropriate) or a curved-but-monotonic trend (where Spearman is larger and more honest); (3) MULTICOLLINEARITY — several predictors strongly correlated with each other is a warning for any regression that uses them together. Correlation is not causation, and a near-zero coefficient only rules out a MONOTONIC relationship, not any relationship. Pearson (1895); Spearman (1904).",
